 and through many familiar antinomies: local and global,micro and macroevents to name a few. Even the most critical among us often proceed with our analysis as if such scales were the ready-made platforms of social life, rather than asking how, why, and to what effect are scalar distinctions forged in the first place. How do scalar distinctions help actors and analysts alike make sense of and navigate their social worlds? What do these distinctions reveal and what do they conceal? How are scales construed and what effects do they have on the way those who abide by them think and act? This pathbreaking volume attends to the practical labor of scale-making and the communicative practices this labor requires. From an ethnographic perspective, the authors demonstrate that scale is practice and process before it becomes product, whether in the work of projecting the commons, claiming access to the big picture, or scaling the seriousness of a crime.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aScaling (Social sciences). 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh1 aBauman, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarr, E. Summerson, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFisher, Brooke, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGal, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIrvine, Judith T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLempert, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLempert, Michael, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMeek, Barbra A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocab